# gen142 (E7): local-world working memory. A TEMPORARY, named scope for a
# fiction or task. Facts introduced "in this story" live in a session overlay,
# are usable in later turns, can be inspected ("what is assumed?"), and tear down
# cleanly — nothing leaks into permanent memory (the KB).

# 1. Enter a scope with an inline clause; the fact lands in the world overlay.
> in this story rex is a dragon
< In the story world, rex is a dragon.

# 2. The world fact is usable on a later turn.
> is rex a dragon?
< Yes.

# 3. "what is assumed?" reads the active overlay back — grounded, not canned.
> what is assumed?
< In the story world I am assuming: rex is a dragon.

# 4. "who is X?" lists X's classes in this world.
> who is rex?
< In the story world, rex is a dragon.

# 5. A class never assumed in this world is honestly unknown, not false.
> is rex a knight?
< Not assumed in the story world.

# 6. A second turn can extend the same world.
> rex is a hero
< In the story world, rex is a hero.

# 7. Tearing the world down drops exactly its facts; nothing reached memory, so
#    the same query is now unknown at the permanent layer (no leak).
> forget this world
< Forgotten the story world; none of it reached my memory.
> is rex a dragon?
< I don't know about dragon.
